<!--how it works section-->
<div class="container mb-2" id="howitworks" style="height:88vh;">
    <h2 class="text-justified text-success bg-dark">How It Works</h2>
    <br>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h5 class="text-center"><u>Frontend Logic</u></h5>
            <p class="text-justified text-secondary"> The moment a user submits a theme selection, a jquery <strong>click</strong> event listener is triggered, which the makes a 
                <em>GET</em> request to the server either via XHttp, ajax or fetch function, depending on the submit button clicked by the user.
                Being asynchronous, ajax and fetch functions waits for the server's response data. Looping through the theme object name and cdn properties (server response data ), using
                an identifier passed as a callback parameter, if a name matches the value of the intial ui design selected, the respective theme  bootswatch cdn
                is then set as the <code>&lt;link src=""&gt;</code> attribute for the first Link child of the head element using jquery for all the pages.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6 border-left border-secondary">
            <h5 class="text-center"><u>Backend Logic</u></h5>
            <p class="text-justified text-secondary">
                All request are served back to the client using node.Js fs and path modules. Once a <i>"/theme"</i> request gets to the server; the server checks within the application directory for 
                a <b>themes.json file</b>, that contains an object of the different themes in the app directory and sends back the data in the file as response for further client-side processing.
                A simple Switch conditional is used to set the appropraite content-type header for response sent back to the client.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>                
</div>

